  "text": "The Node.js child_process module implements comprehensive command injection prevention through multiple layers of validation. The primary entry points are in lib/child_process.js: spawn(), exec(), execFile(), fork(), execSync(), execFileSync(), and spawnSync(). These functions normalize and validate all user-supplied arguments through the normalizeSpawnArguments() function (line 538), which performs critical null-byte validation on the file path, command arguments, environment variables, and other parameters. The validateArgumentNullCheck() function (line 963) checks if a string contains null bytes (\\u0000) and throws an ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE error if detected, preventing null-byte injection attacks. validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 970) applies this validation to arrays of arguments. Specifically, in normalizeSpawnArguments(), validation occurs on: the file parameter (line 540), all args (line 556), argv0 option (line 597), shell option (line 613), and environment variable keys and values (lines 691-692). The fork() function also validates execPath and execArgv arguments (lines 142, 146). The exec() and execFile() functions normalize arguments through normalizeExecArgs() and normalizeExecFileArgs() which also validate against null bytes. The JavaScript ChildProcess class in lib/internal/child_process.js (line 254) wraps the native Process binding and delegates process creation to its spawn() method (line 354), which passes validated options to the native layer via this._handle.spawn(options) (line 395). The native ProcessWrap C++ class in src/process_wrap.cc implements the low-level process spawning. The ProcessWrap::Spawn() method (line 153) receives the validated options from JavaScript and uses uv_spawn() to create the child process, ensuring that all arguments have already been validated for null bytes at the JavaScript layer. For synchronous operations, src/spawn_sync.cc provides the SyncProcessOutputBuffer and SyncProcessStdioPipe classes for handling synchronous process spawning while maintaining the same argument validation guarantees through the normalizeSpawnArguments() validation applied before calling the native spawn_sync binding."
}

